  "prompt": "Does my H1B visa transfer impact my spouse's H4 visa?",
  "response": "Yes, your H1B visa transfer can impact your spouse's H4 visa, but the process is usually straightforward if handled correctly. Here\u2019s how it typically works:\n\n1. **H1B Transfer Approval**: Once your new employer files an H1B transfer petition (Form I-129) and it is approved, your H1B status is transferred to the new employer. Your spouse\u2019s H4 status is dependent on your H1B status.\n\n2. **H4 Status**: If your spouse is already in the U.S. on an H4 visa and your H1B transfer is approved, their H4 status remains valid as long as your H1B status is valid. They do not need to take any immediate action unless they plan to travel internationally.\n\n3. **Travel Outside the U.S.**:\n   - If your spouse travels outside the U.S. after your H1B transfer is approved, they will need a new H4 visa stamp based on your new H1B approval notice (Form I-797) from the new employer to re-enter the U.S.\n   - If they do not travel outside the U.S., they do not need to apply for a new H4 visa stamp immediately.\n\n4. **H4 EAD (Employment Authorization Document)**: If your spouse holds an H4 EAD based on your previous H1B, they will need to apply for a new H4 EAD based on the new H1B approval notice. The H4 EAD is tied to your specific H1B status, so a transfer requires a new application.\n\n5. **Timing**: Ensure that your H1B transfer is filed before your current H1B status expires to maintain lawful status for both you and your spouse.\n\nTo summarize, your H1B transfer does impact your spouse\u2019s H4 status, but they will remain in valid H4 status as long as your H1B transfer is approved. If they travel internationally or hold an H4 EAD, additional steps may be required. Always consult an immigration attorney for personalized advice.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
